---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="FraiseQL for Enterprise SaaS - Multi-Tenant, RBAC, Performance"
  description="Use case: Multi-tenant SaaS platforms with role-based access control."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>🏢 Enterprise SaaS: Multi-Tenant Platforms</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>Database-first multi-tenancy with strong isolation and deterministic performance</strong>
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Challenge</h2>
      <p>
        Enterprise SaaS requires:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tenant isolation:</strong> Customer A can't see Customer B's data</li>
        <li><strong>Role-based access:</strong> Admin vs Editor vs Viewer permissions</li>
        <li><strong>Deterministic performance:</strong> Fair usage across all tenants</li>
        <li><strong>Audit trail:</strong> Know who changed what in which tenant</li>
        <li><strong>Multi-database:</strong> Flexibility to host different tenant types</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>FraiseQL Multi-Tenant Architecture</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Database-Per-Tenant</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Each tenant gets separate database
tenant-acme → postgres://acme.example.com/acme_db
tenant-globex → postgres://globex.example.com/globex_db
tenant-initech → postgres://initech.example.com/initech_db

# At compile time:
fraiseql compile schema.json fraiseql.toml

# At runtime:
# 1. User provides JWT with tenant_id
# 2. Server routes to tenant's database connection
# 3. Executes pre-compiled query
# 4. Returns results isolated to tenant

# Result: Perfect isolation, no data leakage possible`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Row-Level Security (RLS)</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Alternative: All tenants share database, but rows are isolated

@fraiseql.type
class Document:
    id: int
    tenant_id: int  # Row-level tenant_id
    name: str
    content: str @encrypted

# Query automatically filters by tenant
query GetDocuments {
  documents {
    # Only returns docs where tenant_id == current_user.tenant_id
  }
}

# At compile time:
# - Compiler verifies tenant_id is always filtered
# - Prevents accidental cross-tenant queries

# Result: Multiple tenants in one database, isolated by compiled constraints`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)</h2>

      <pre><code>{`# Define roles and permissions
@fraiseql.type
class User:
    id: int
    name: str
    role: str  # "admin", "editor", "viewer"

@fraiseql.type
class Document:
    id: int
    title: str
    content: str

# Control field visibility by role
@rbac(roles=["admin", "editor"])
@fraiseql.mutation
def update_document_content(id: int, content: str) -> Document:
    # Only admin or editor can update
    pass

@rbac(roles=["admin"])
@fraiseql.mutation
def delete_document(id: int) -> Boolean:
    # Only admin can delete
    pass

@rbac(roles=["admin", "editor", "viewer"])
query get_document($id: ID!) {
  # Everyone can read
}

# Verification: Compiler enforces permissions at build time
# No permission leaks possible at runtime`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Example: Project Management SaaS</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Company:</strong> TaskMaster, enterprise project management platform
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Challenge:</strong> Support 10,000 customers with varying database preferences. Some want PostgreSQL, others MySQL.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">FraiseQL Solution</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Single schema, multi-database support
schema.json:
  organizations: List[Organization]
  projects: List[Project]
  tasks: List[Task]

# Tenant 1-1000: PostgreSQL (hosted at AWS)
# Tenant 1001-5000: MySQL (hosted at GCP)
# Tenant 5001-10000: PostgreSQL (on-premise)

# At compile time:
fraiseql compile schema.json --for-postgres
fraiseql compile schema.json --for-mysql

# At runtime:
# User from Tenant 2500 (MySQL):
# - JWT token: tenant_id=2500
# - Server routes to MySQL database
# - Executes pre-compiled MySQL query
# - Returns result

# User from Tenant 7500 (PostgreSQL):
# - JWT token: tenant_id=7500
# - Server routes to PostgreSQL database
# - Executes pre-compiled PostgreSQL query
# - Returns result

# Same schema, different databases, perfect isolation`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Audit Trail Per Tenant</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Every mutation is tracked by tenant
query AuditLog($tenant_id: ID!) {
  audit_log(tenant_id: $tenant_id) {
    timestamp
    user_id
    action
    changes
  }
}

# Result:
# - Tenant A sees only their mutations
# - Tenant B sees only their mutations
# - Cross-tenant leakage impossible (compiler enforces)`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Performance: Per-Tenant Isolation</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>No noisy neighbor:</strong> Tenant A's high load doesn't affect Tenant B
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Deterministic latency:</strong> Each tenant sees 1-2ms query latency
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Independent scaling:</strong> Scale each tenant's database independently
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Result</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>✅ 10,000 customers on single FraiseQL cluster</li>
        <li>✅ Perfect tenant isolation (no data leakage incidents)</li>
        <li>✅ Multi-database support (PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite)</li>
        <li>✅ Audit trail per tenant for compliance</li>
        <li>✅ 99.9% uptime (deterministic performance)</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Advanced Patterns</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">1. Organization Hierarchy</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Support nested organizations (org → team → user)
@fraiseql.type
class Organization:
    id: int
    name: str
    teams: List[Team]

@fraiseql.type
class Team:
    id: int
    org_id: int
    name: str
    members: List[User]

# Access control:
# - Org admin can see all teams and users
# - Team member can see only their team
# - Compiler enforces these constraints`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">2. Workspace Sharing</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Users can be invited to multiple workspaces
# Each workspace has separate data

query GetUserWorkspaces {
  my_workspaces {
    id
    name
    role  # User's role in this workspace
  }
}

query GetWorkspaceData($workspace_id: ID!) {
  workspace(id: $workspace_id) {
    # Returns only if user has access
  }
}

# At compile time:
# - Compiler verifies user.workspaces is checked
# - Prevents accidental cross-workspace queries`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">3. Billing & Rate Limiting per Tenant</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Different rate limits per customer tier

[fraiseql.security.rate_limiting]
# Default (free tier)
max_requests = 100
window_secs = 60

# Can be overridden per tenant:
"tenant-acme" = { max_requests = 10000, window_secs = 60 }  # Premium
"tenant-globex" = { max_requests = 1000, window_secs = 60 }  # Pro`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Migration Strategy</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>How to migrate existing SaaS to FraiseQL:</strong>
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Phase 1:</strong> Deploy FraiseQL alongside current GraphQL server
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Phase 2:</strong> Canary: Route 5% of traffic to FraiseQL
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Phase 3:</strong> Monitor: Compare latency, errors, audit trails
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Phase 4:</strong> Roll out: Increase traffic to 50%, 100%
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Phase 5:</strong> Decommission: Turn off old GraphQL server
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <strong>Timeline:</strong> 2-4 weeks (with proper testing and validation)
      </p>
    </section>

